node.text:
It’s been a long time since I’ve tried @oldnavy denim jeans but I knew I had to with their new #BODEQUALITY designs bringing in a range of sizes from 0-30, petite + tall, with no price differences and designed for more than just one body type! 

Now at Old Navy there’s no more plus size section, we all shop together, in-store and online with variable mannequins and models to show different sizes! And again, NO price difference! 

At a size 12, my body doesn’t need jeans designed for a size 2 and vice versa. Same with a 22 or a 4 or whatever size! So they’re designed with different bodies in mind. 

I was FLOORED when these just ✨fit✨
If you know my journey with denim jeans postpartum then you freaking KNOW the deal this is. 

Not just denim! Sweaters, Activewear (powersoft fans I see you👀) dresses and more. 🙌

Excited to see this step happening, for fashion (and comfort) lovers everywhere. 

@oldnavy #BODEQUALITY #ad

node.text:
Lately I have felt called for speak into my experience with prenatal depression. Something I never saw coming or knew could even happen. After birth and through therapy I was able to come through it, but that’s not everyone’s story. It doesn’t end at birth for many like mine did. 

Here are some more stats. 
TW: suicide discussion 

1 in 7 experience depression in pregnancy. 
1 in 5 will suffer from maternal mental health disorder like postpartum depression or anxiety. 
1 in 7 maternal deaths between 6 weeks pregnant and 1 year postpartum die by suicide. (Read that again!) 
Rates of depression are more than doubled for black mothers. 
1 in 10 dads will experience perinatal mental health disorders. 
Less than 15% will receive treatment. 

If you are struggling with perinatal mental health,  feel like you’re supposed to be happy but just aren’t, numb, anxious or struggling to connect, consider talking to someone. 

It’s not your fault you feel this way. 

#suicidepreventionmonth

node.text:
Spend time with with those who see you for more than your body. ⁣
⁣
Feel how your shoulders relax. ⁣
Note how you stopped worrying about what you will eat, or wear. ⁣
Recognize how the conversations flow differently, positively. ⁣
Acknowledge your differences and your likeness. ⁣
See the beauty in each of you. ⁣
Hold onto the fact that it looks and feels so different for each of you. ⁣
⁣
Then, almost like magic, you will start seeing yourself as a human with contributions that are more than a body, after all. ⁣

@choosingchelsea @kristinazias @arielleestoria @raeannlangas @fittybritttty

node.text:
We are not broken or ruined or destroyed. 
But built and bloomed and evolved. 

We are not going backwards. 
But most certainly moving forwards.

We have not lost our bodies. 
But truly in and with them right now. 

We are not grounds for wreckage. 
But grounds for celebration. 

There will be grief days. 
There will be joyful ones too. 

But we will move forward, our bodies carrying us there, through each and every feeling, and each and every twist and turn. 

Just showing up. 
Again and again. 

So that one day, maybe, we don’t search in fear of what may come to be and instead search in awe of what we may become.

node.text:
And that’s a wrap on summer!

With the last week we crammed as much of it in as we could. We are all exhausted. Ready for bed, but not quite ready to put summer to rest. 

We have zero family photos but hundreds of new memories I’ll cherish forever from this last week. So grateful for this time and this season with them all. 

Rooting for everyone tucking in tired kids tonite, backing bags and labelling everything, pushing their anxiety into their pocket while helping them out the door and into a new chapter… we got this. We really do. Even when it’s chaos and unknowns. 🤍

node.text:
Neither of us will remember this day for the dimples on my thighs, the size of my waist or the stretch marks on my skin. 

We will remember this day for her toes in the sand. Seeing her first wave. Picking up rocks. Swimming with her sister. Experiencing a beach together. Being there. Just being there. That’s enough. 

It’s so easy to forget,
The things we catch and the things we release. 

We catch the good stuff. 
The meaningful memories. 
Like how good it felt to soak in that moment. 

We release the moments not serving us. 
Like the insecurities we carry on the day we did. 

I have to think more like this lately. Measuring and thinking on projections into the future. What WILL I remember? What do I WANT to remember? What do I want to be remembered FOR? 

Because when I think back on my own childhood and think about my mother, I carry no memories of her thighs or stretch marks or waist size. I just carry the good stuff. Her being there. Just being there. That’s enough. 

So yeah. I guess what I’m trying to say is, I know and I’ve been feeling how hard it can be in the moment, it’s hard to escape the feelings. 
But in the long haul, they don’t follow me. 

Catch and carry the good stuff. 
Release the rest.

node.text:
I thought the realization that fairy tales aren’t reality would mean a life filled with less love. Or at least, a love less great. 

Instead what it meant was that I could take the role of a great love myself. 

I could be whole, no longer waiting on a half. 

So that every decision and relationship since would build into me. Would help build me up. Help support me. And I them. 

Not a burden to be lifted up. 
But collectively, a unit to be held. 

A family. 

Just not the kind I would ever know in stories and fairy tales, anyways. 

The kind that we build. 
On our own terms. 
In our own way. 
5 whole units, choosing life together. 

This love. 
It is so big. 
It started with me. 
And them. 
Then him. 

And it really has been, just the best. 

Happy anniversary, my love. To us🤍
